 used legal liability, lawsuit-generated publicity, and innovative managerial ideas to pursue the implementation of new rights. Together, these strategies resulted in frameworks designed to make institutions accountable through intricate rules, employee training, and managerial oversight. Explaining how these practices became ubiquitous across bureaucratic organizations, Epp casts today’s legalistic state in an entirely new light.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCivil rightsxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCivil rightsxHistoryy20th centuryxUnited States. 0aCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLaw reformxCitizen participationxUnited States. 0aLaw reformzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aLiability (Law)xUnited States. 0aLiability (Law)zUnited States. 0aLiability for harassmentxUnited States. 0aLiability for harassmentzUnited States. 0aPlaygroundsxLaw and legislationxUnited StatesxGreat BritainxUnited States. 0aPlaygroundsxLaw and legislationzGreat BritainxUnited States. 0aPlaygroundsxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aTort liability of policexGreat Britain. 0aTort liability of policexUnited States. 0aTort liability of policezGreat Britain. 0aTort liability of policezUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acivil rights, law enforcement, government, legal system, police brutality, playground safety, workplace sexual harassment, regulation, laws, accountability, publicity, lawsuits, liability, bureaucracy, oversight, employee training, rules, reform, torts, racial bias, racism, profiling, discrimination, nonfiction, history, politics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Packag